SIMPLE: loco
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Loco
<hw>Lo"co</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[It.]</ety>
<fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A direction in written or printed music to return
to the proper pitch after having played an octave higher.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loco</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Loco
<hw>Lo"co</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>loco</ets> insane.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A plant (<spn>Astragalus
Hornii</spn>) growing in the Southwestern United States, which is said
to poison horses and cattle, first making them insane. The name is also
given vaguely to several other species of the same genus. Called also
<altname>loco weed</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Any one of various leguminous
plants or weeds besides <gen>Astragalus</gen>, whose herbage is
poisonous to cattle, as <spn>Spiesia Lambertii</spn>, syn.
<spn>Oxytropis Lambertii</spn>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loco</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Loco
<hw>Lo"co</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Locoed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Locoing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To poison with loco; to affect
with the loco disease; hence (<mark>Colloq.</mark>), to render insane or
mad.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>locoed</xex> novelist.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>W. D.
Howells.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loco</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Loco
<hw>Lo"co</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A locomotive.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <rj><au>Kipling.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>loco</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: loco
<hw>lo"co</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>loco</ets> insane.]</ety>
<def>Insane; crazy.</def> <mark>[Originally Southwestern U. S., now
slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loco disease</ent>⟦br⟧
